# üêû bug report

### Affected Package
@angular/*** 9.1.9


### Is this a regression?

Probably


### Description

#### Prerequisite :
Create a component with two `@Input`, one of them is a setter method (it propably does not matter but having a method helps to see the problem).
Let's call "value1" the Input using a setter method and "value2" the Input applied directly on a property.


```ts
@Component({
  selector: 'hello',
  template: `
    setValue called {{count}} times<br>
    value1 : {{value1}}<br>
    value2 : {{value2}}
  `,
})
export class HelloComponent  {

  value1: any;
  count = 0;

  @Input('value1')
  set setValue1(value: any) {
    this.value1 = value;
    this.count++;
  }

  @Input() value2: any;

}
``` 

#### Use it :
Use this component in a view with this configuration
- "value1" is a direct binding to a constant
- "value2" uses an Observable + async pipe + optional chaining

```ts
@Component({
  selector: 'my-app',
  template: `
  <hello [value1]="value1" [value2]="(value2$ | async)?.i"></hello>
  `,
})
export class AppComponent  {

  value1 = 'value 1';

  value2$ = timer(1000, 1000)
    .pipe(map(i => ({i})));

}
```

#### What happens :
Everytime "value2" changes, the setter method of "value1" is called, although the value didn't changed.
**If you remove the optional chaining there is no problem.**

After a long debugging session in the change detector I tracked down the problem to this line
https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/master/packages/core/src/render3/pipe.ts#L221
where "bindingToInvalidateIdx" is for some reason the index of "value1" and not "value2". Because of this when the change detector runs for "value1" the old value is "NO_CHANGE" and not the actual value, hence refreshing the input.

## üî¨ Minimal Reproduction

https://stackblitz.com/edit/angular-ivy-xkcbs1

In the setter of "value1" I increment a counter, this counter is increment when "value2" changes.

## üåç  Your Environment

**Angular Version:**
<pre><code>
    "@angular/animations": "9.1.9",
    "@angular/common": "9.1.9",
    "@angular/compiler": "9.1.9",
    "@angular/core": "9.1.9",
    "@angular/forms": "9.1.9",
    "@angular/platform-browser": "9.1.9",
    "@angular/platform-browser-dynamic": "9.1.9",
    "@angular/router": "9.1.9",
    "@angular-devkit/build-angular": "0.901.7",
    "@angular/cli": "9.1.7",
    "@angular/compiler-cli": "9.1.9",
</code></pre>

when applying a template, using an absolute path to templates location, it causes an error
```
...
return (tree,context){
 var source = url( __dirname + "/files" ); //using full path here causes an Error,
 var template = apply( source , [...] )
 return mergeWith(template, strategy);

//->Error: Unknown Protocol on url "[object Object]".
}
```

**use case**
if the schematics uses an external file that is not listed in collection.json to apply some rules, the template path here will be relative to the function, not the schematic function witch is wrong.

```
...
const getRule = require('./path/to/function')

return (tree,context){ 
 return getRule();
//->Error: Unknown Protocol on url "[object Object]".
}
```
```
function getRule(){
 //this is relative to the function which is in another location away from the schematic path
//the function dosen't know about the schematic location
 var source = url(  "/.files" );
 var template = apply( source , [...] )
 return mergeWith(template, strategy);
}
```
angular schematics will resolve this path relatively to the schematic location, but it is retative to the function location, then it will not find any template files.

there is a workaround, is to create a relative path between the schematic path and the template path.

```
function getRule(context){
var sourcePath = path.relative(
      context.schematic.description.path,
     path. join(__dirname, "./templates")
    )

 var source = url(  "/.files" );
...
}
```

but if the schematics started from a different drive (c:/) than the template location (D:/), then `path.relative()`
will return the absolute path which will fail again.

I reported this issue as bug rather than feature request, because it causes error in this case.
if it is incorrect label, feel free to change it.

## Proposal

Add for [MatTextareaAutosize](https://material.angular.io/components/input/api#MatTextareaAutosize) Callback with height and return custom sum and set it as height for textarea element.

```
CdkTextareaAutosize {
  ...
  // Options by default parameter emitEvent is false
  setHeight(height: number, {emitEvent: boolean}): void;

  // Return number after calculation height textarea element
  heightChanges(): Observable<number>;
  ...
}
```
